<i>In Thneedville,
we love living this way</i>

38
00:03:50,380 --> 00:03:53,800
<i>It's like living in paradise</i>

39
00:03:53,884 --> 00:03:56,803
<i>It's perfect!
And that's how it will stay</i>

40
00:03:56,887 --> 00:03:57,971
<i>Oh, yeah!</i>

41
00:03:58,054 --> 00:04:00,640
<i>Here in
Love-the-life-we-lead-ville</i>

42
00:04:00,724 --> 00:04:02,475
<i>Destined-to-succeed-ville</i>

43
00:04:02,559 --> 00:04:04,644
<i>We-are-all-agreed-ville</i>

44
00:04:04,728 --> 00:04:07,814
<i>We love it here in...</i>

45
00:04:09,774 --> 00:04:11,443
<i>Thneedville!</i>

46
00:04:51,107 --> 00:04:52,400
Yes!

47
00:05:07,290 --> 00:05:08,375
Oh, hi, Ted.

48
00:05:09,626 --> 00:05:11,836
Oh, hey, Audrey. Hi.

49
00:05:12,128 --> 00:05:14,798
Did your ball land
in my backyard again?

50
00:05:14,923 --> 00:05:16,383
What? No.

51
00:05:16,633 --> 00:05:18,426
A model airplane, this time.

52
00:05:19,469 --> 00:05:21,846
Hey, do you want to
see something cool?

53
00:05:22,013 --> 00:05:23,181
Come on.

54
00:05:29,396 --> 00:05:31,147
Whoa!

55
00:05:37,904 --> 00:05:39,447
Did you...

56
00:05:39,739 --> 00:05:41,616
Did you paint this?

57
00:05:41,741 --> 00:05:43,618
Do you like it?
What?

58
00:05:43,952 --> 00:05:47,539
Are you kidding?
This is amazing!

59
00:05:47,789 --> 00:05:48,873
What are those?

60
00:05:48,957 --> 00:05:52,085
Those are trees.
Real ones.

61
00:05:52,377 --> 00:05:55,463
They used to grow
all around here.

62
00:05:56,381 --> 00:05:59,259
And people said that
the touch of their tufts

63
00:05:59,342 --> 00:06:01,886
was softer than
anything, even silk.

64
00:06:02,137 --> 00:06:04,722
And they smelled
like butterfly milk!

65
00:06:04,806 --> 00:06:07,016
Wow! What does
that even mean?

66
00:06:07,308 --> 00:06:08,518
I know, right?

67
00:06:10,895 --> 00:06:11,980
Oh, yeah.

68
00:06:12,063 --> 00:06:15,567
What I want more than anything
in the whole world is to see

69
00:06:16,025 --> 00:06:18,111
a real living tree

70
00:06:18,820 --> 00:06:19,988
growing in my backyard.

71
00:06:20,363 --> 00:06:23,116
So if, say... I'm just
thinking out loud here.

72
00:06:23,199 --> 00:06:25,952
If a guy somehow got you one...

73
00:06:26,161 --> 00:06:28,329
I'd probably
marry him on the spot.

74
00:06:28,788 --> 00:06:31,166
I bet that sounds crazy.
Does that sound crazy?

75
00:06:31,416 --> 00:06:33,251
No! Not crazy.

76
00:06:33,710 --> 00:06:35,670
Not crazy at all.

77
00:06:42,844 --> 00:06:45,555
Ted, honey,
don't play with your food.

78
00:06:45,722 --> 00:06:47,015
You, either, Mom.

79
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:56,649
So, Mom, do you happen to
know if there's any place

80
00:06:56,816 --> 00:06:59,235
where I could get a real tree?

81
00:06:59,402 --> 00:07:02,155
Ted, we already have a tree.
It's the latest model.

82
00:07:02,405 --> 00:07:04,616
Yeah, but I mean a real one

83
00:07:04,699 --> 00:07:07,785
that grows out of
the ground or whatever.

84
00:07:07,869 --> 00:07:09,370
You know, a real tree.

85
00:07:09,537 --> 00:07:10,580
Really?

86
00:07:10,663 --> 00:07:13,499
You would rather
have some dirty, messy

87
00:07:13,750 --> 00:07:16,085
lump of wood that just
sticks out of the ground?

88
00:07:16,169 --> 00:07:17,545
And it does what? I don't
even know what it does.

89
00:07:17,629 --> 00:07:18,755
What's its purpose?

90
00:07:18,838 --> 00:07:20,131
Look at what we've got.

91
00:07:20,215 --> 00:07:23,509
It's the Oak-amatic. The only
tree with its own remote.

92
00:07:23,885 --> 00:07:26,638
Summer, autumn, winter,

93
00:07:26,721 --> 00:07:27,931
and disco!

94
00:07:32,769 --> 00:07:34,395
Mom? Come on, Ted. Get into it.

95
00:07:34,479 --> 00:07:35,563
Dance with the tree.

96
00:07:35,647 --> 00:07:37,690
Oh, it hurts, Mom. Please stop.

97
00:07:38,232 --> 00:07:40,234
So' anyway...

98
00:07:40,360 --> 00:07:42,195
Let's just say I need a tree.

99
00:07:42,278 --> 00:07:43,863
Where would I go?
What do I do?

100
00:07:44,072 --> 00:07:47,075
Then you know what? You
need to find the Once-ler.

101
00:07:48,117 --> 00:07:49,160
The what?

102
00:07:49,243 --> 00:07:54,499
Mom, it's not really the time for
one of your magical fables, okay?

103
00:07:54,791 --> 00:07:56,876
That's right, I forgot.

104
00:07:57,085 --> 00:08:00,546
I'm old and can't even
remember to put my teeth in.

105
00:08:00,797 --> 00:08:02,590
Stand down.
That's not what I meant.

106
00:08:02,674 --> 00:08:04,634
No, really, I forgot my teeth.

107
00:08:04,926 --> 00:08:07,512
Would you be a dear
and go get them for me?

108
00:08:07,595 --> 00:08:09,514
Sure, Mom.

109
00:08:16,104 --> 00:08:17,313
Okay, here's the deal.

110
00:08:17,480 --> 00:08:20,525
The Once-ler is the man who knows
what happened to the trees.

111
00:08:20,608 --> 00:08:22,944
You want one,
you need to find him.

112
00:08:23,027 --> 00:08:25,697
The Once-ler?
Mmm-hmm.

113
00:08:25,780 --> 00:08:28,199
Okay. Grammy,
is this a real thing

114
00:08:28,282 --> 00:08:29,659
that we're talking about now?

115
00:08:29,784 --> 00:08:31,452
Oh, he's real all right.

116
00:08:31,786 --> 00:08:33,538
Well, where can I find him?

117
00:08:36,249 --> 00:08:40,294
Far outside of town
where the grass never grows

118
00:08:40,586 --> 00:08:44,132
and the wind smells slow
and sour when it blows.

119
00:08:46,467 --> 00:08:50,680
And no birds ever sing,
excepting old crows.

120
00:08:53,808 --> 00:08:54,976
Quit doing that.

121
00:08:55,101 --> 00:08:57,520
That's the place
where the Once-ler lives.

122
00:08:57,603 --> 00:08:59,939
Wait, outside of town?

123
00:09:00,857 --> 00:09:04,485
People used to say
if you brought him 15 cents,

124
00:09:04,652 --> 00:09:05,695
<i>a nail</i>

125
00:09:05,945 --> 00:09:09,866
<i>and the shell of a great,
great, great grandfather snail,</i>

126
00:09:11,826 --> 00:09:14,662
<i>he would tell you everything.</i>

127
00:09:44,692 --> 00:09:45,735
Hmm.

128
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:19,685
Mr. O'Hare,
what we've got for you

129
00:10:19,769 --> 00:10:22,063
is something that is
going to take O'Hare Air

130
00:10:22,230 --> 00:10:23,898
to the next level.

131
00:10:24,106 --> 00:10:25,983
Now, Mr. O'Hare,
I know what you're thinking.

132
00:10:26,067 --> 00:10:28,194
One, "I've gotten rich
selling people air that's"

133
00:10:28,277 --> 00:10:30,363
"fresher than
the stinky stuff outside"

134
00:10:30,446 --> 00:10:32,073
Two, and here is
the important one,

135
00:10:32,156 --> 00:10:34,575
"How can I possibly make
even more money?"

136
00:10:34,784 --> 00:10:36,577
We can tell you, sir!
We can tell you.

137
00:10:36,744 --> 00:10:39,413
Check out this commercial, huh?

138
00:10:41,958 --> 00:10:44,377
Well, here goes
another lame Saturday.

139
00:10:44,961 --> 00:10:47,922
Dude, I don't think so!

140
00:10:49,423 --> 00:10:50,508
Huh!

141
00:10:51,592 --> 00:10:52,718
Hey!

142
00:10:55,304 --> 00:10:56,347
Man!

143
00:10:56,430 --> 00:10:57,515
Oh, yeah!

144
00:10:58,474 --> 00:10:59,600
What!

145
00:11:03,270 --> 00:11:04,480
Yeah!

146
00:11:05,147 --> 00:11:07,942
<i>O'Hare purified air.
Freshness to go.</i>

147
00:11:08,025 --> 00:11:09,360
<i>Please breathe responsibly.</i>

148
00:11:09,443 --> 00:11:10,569
Ah?

149
00:11:10,653 --> 00:11:12,405
Oh, my goodness. Yeah!
Love it.

150
00:11:12,947 --> 00:11:14,907
You got to be kidding me.

151
00:11:14,991 --> 00:11:17,952
You really think people are
stupid enough to buy this?

152
00:11:18,244 --> 00:11:21,706
Our research shows that if you put
something in a plastic bottle,

153
00:11:21,789 --> 00:11:22,957
people will buy it.

154
00:11:23,040 --> 00:11:24,166
Exactly. And...

155
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:26,252
And what's more, when
we build a new factory

156
00:11:26,335 --> 00:11:27,920
to make the plastic bottles,

157
00:11:28,045 --> 00:11:30,506
the air quality is
just going to get worse.

158
00:11:30,715 --> 00:11:32,717
Which will make people
want our air even more,

159
00:11:32,800 --> 00:11:34,760
and drive sales where?

160
00:11:34,885 --> 00:11:35,928
Through the roof!

161
00:11:36,220 --> 00:11:40,641
So, in other words,
the more smog in the sky

162
00:11:42,518 --> 00:11:43,978
the more people will buy.

163
00:11:46,188 --> 00:11:49,608
See, that's why he's the genius!
It even rhymes!

164
00:11:50,443 --> 00:11:52,445
I'm aware it rhymes.

165
00:11:53,362 --> 00:11:54,488
Coats. Big.

166
00:11:54,572 --> 00:11:56,073
What do you two
knuckleheads want?

167
00:11:56,157 --> 00:11:57,616
I'm in the middle of a meeting!

168
00:12:00,619 --> 00:12:01,704
What?

169
00:12:01,996 --> 00:12:03,456
Why is he leaving town?

170
00:12:03,581 --> 00:12:05,499
No one ever leaves town!

171
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:07,626
See what he's up to.

172
00:12:18,929 --> 00:12:20,264
Whoa!

173
00:13:12,191 --> 00:13:13,317
Huh?

174
00:13:15,152 --> 00:13:16,487
Whoa! Whoa.

175
00:13:19,782 --> 00:13:21,116
Oh, man.

176
00:14:21,343 --> 00:14:22,636
Whoa!

177
00:14:22,928 --> 00:14:24,430
All right.

178
00:15:03,093 --> 00:15:04,178
Okay.

179
00:15:05,012 --> 00:15:07,181
What the...

180
00:15:07,264 --> 00:15:08,766
Whoa!

181
00:15:16,482 --> 00:15:17,566
Who are you?

182
00:15:17,816 --> 00:15:20,068
Who are you and what
are you doing here?

183
00:15:20,235 --> 00:15:22,654
I'm Ted. I'm Ted.

184
00:15:22,905 --> 00:15:25,491
I can't breathe.
Are you the Once-ler?

185
00:15:25,657 --> 00:15:27,868
Oh, man.
Didn't you read the signs?

186
00:15:28,160 --> 00:15:30,287
No one is
supposed to come here.

187
00:15:30,579 --> 00:15:32,581
Get out of here
and leave me alone!

188
00:15:32,664 --> 00:15:34,666
And don't let the boot
hit you on the way out.

189
00:15:34,750 --> 00:15:35,834
The boot?

190
00:15:36,627 --> 00:15:37,669
Hello!

191
00:15:37,753 --> 00:15:38,837
Ow!

192
00:15:39,004 --> 00:15:42,049
Listen! People say that if
someone brings you this stuff

193
00:15:42,341 --> 00:15:44,218
that you will tell
them about trees.

194
00:15:44,593 --> 00:15:45,677
No, no, no!

195
00:15:48,263 --> 00:15:49,473
Trees?

196
00:15:49,681 --> 00:15:51,016
Yeah, real ones.

197
00:15:51,141 --> 00:15:53,852
You know,
that grow out of the ground?

198
00:15:55,354 --> 00:15:56,480
Hello?

199
00:15:56,563 --> 00:15:58,023
Sorry, it's just...

200
00:15:58,190 --> 00:16:00,651
Well, I didn't think anyone
still cared about trees.

201
00:16:00,734 --> 00:16:04,238
Well, that's me. The guy
who still cares. I'm here.

202
00:16:04,404 --> 00:16:06,615
Hey! What?

203
00:16:07,783 --> 00:16:09,159
Do you want to
know about trees?

204
00:16:09,243 --> 00:16:11,578
About what happened to them?

205
00:16:11,745 --> 00:16:15,666
Why they're all gone?
It's because of me.

206
00:16:15,749 --> 00:16:16,792
Wait, what?

207
00:16:22,631 --> 00:16:24,841
It's because of me!

208
00:16:26,927 --> 00:16:30,556
And my invention, the Thneed.

209
00:16:30,931 --> 00:16:35,102
It was an amazing product that
could do the job of a thousand.

210
00:16:36,478 --> 00:16:37,521
All right.

211
00:16:37,980 --> 00:16:39,731
Sounds ridiculous,
but I mean, that's cool.

212
00:16:39,982 --> 00:16:41,942
You're darn right it was cool!

213
00:16:43,110 --> 00:16:45,988
It all started a long time ago.

214
00:16:46,613 --> 00:16:48,240
Can we start not
so long ago, maybe?

215
00:16:48,448 --> 00:16:49,533
Do you want a tree?

216
00:16:49,783 --> 00:16:51,076
Yes, yes.

217
00:16:51,493 --> 00:16:56,790
Then it all started
a long, long time ago.

218
00:16:57,749 --> 00:17:00,460
<i>I was a young man leaving home.</i>

219
00:17:00,544 --> 00:17:04,172
Well, here I go, Mom. Off to
change the world with my Thneed.

220
00:17:06,258 --> 00:17:07,759
I'm actually doing it!

221
00:17:07,843 --> 00:17:10,512
Yes, but just remember, Oncie,

222
00:17:10,679 --> 00:17:13,432
if somehow your invention
ends up a failure

223
00:17:13,515 --> 00:17:15,684
instead of a success,

224
00:17:15,851 --> 00:17:18,228
oh, it wouldn't
surprise me at all!

225
00:17:20,147 --> 00:17:21,315
Nice wheels.

226
00:17:21,815 --> 00:17:22,899
Burn!

227
00:17:23,233 --> 00:17:25,068
Ow!

228
00:17:25,152 --> 00:17:26,320
Yeah, "Burn!"

229
00:17:26,486 --> 00:17:29,698
But you will see, okay? I'm
going to prove you all wrong.

230
00:17:29,823 --> 00:17:31,241
Come on, Melvin!

231
00:17:31,658 --> 00:17:34,202
<i>So, there I was
at the very bottom.</i>

232
00:17:34,286 --> 00:17:36,580
<i>With nothing
but a wagon, a mule,</i>

233
00:17:36,872 --> 00:17:40,959
<i>and a completely irrational
sense of optimism.</i>

234
00:17:45,672 --> 00:17:47,049
<i>I was searching the globe,</i>

235
00:17:47,299 --> 00:17:50,635
<i>obsessed with finding the
perfect material for my Thneed.</i>

236
00:17:53,013 --> 00:17:56,099
<i>But I'd had
absolutely no success.</i>

237
00:17:56,349 --> 00:18:01,146
<i>Until one day, I found paradise.</i>

238
00:18:01,313 --> 00:18:02,355
Oh!

239
00:18:02,439 --> 00:18:04,816
We're going to be
there soon, I'm sure.

240
00:18:05,025 --> 00:18:06,109
Whoa!

241
00:18:15,202 --> 00:18:19,915
This is the most
beautiful place,

242
00:18:20,082 --> 00:18:22,000
okay, I have ever seen.

243
00:18:23,710 --> 00:18:24,920
Oh.

244
00:18:25,003 --> 00:18:26,546
Ta-da!

245
00:18:28,215 --> 00:18:29,299
Whoa!

246
00:19:00,747 --> 00:19:02,666
<i>Yeah</i>

247
00:19:02,833 --> 00:19:04,709
<i>This is it</i>

248
00:19:07,087 --> 00:19:10,090
<i>This is the place</i>

249
00:19:10,590 --> 00:19:15,095
<i>These Truff ula trees
are just what I need</i>

250
00:19:15,262 --> 00:19:20,267
<i>Gonna chop one down
and make my Thneed</i>

251
00:19:21,476 --> 00:19:23,144
<i>But first...</i>

252
00:19:27,607 --> 00:19:28,692
Now you!

253
00:19:31,361 --> 00:19:32,612
That's great!

254
00:19:43,999 --> 00:19:46,585
<i>So now our friendship can begin</i>

255
00:19:46,668 --> 00:19:48,962
<i>Hand in hand, and wing and fin</i>

256
00:19:49,045 --> 00:19:51,715
<i>There's nothing
you and I can't do</i>

257
00:19:51,798 --> 00:19:54,759
<i>So let's all make
my dreams come true</i>

258
00:20:16,323 --> 00:20:17,657
Hey, guys!

259
00:20:18,158 --> 00:20:20,910
Come on, where is
my back-up chorus?

260
00:20:23,330 --> 00:20:24,456
What?

261
00:20:25,999 --> 00:20:27,876
Ah-ha! Oh.

262
00:20:34,841 --> 00:20:36,217
Ooh!

263
00:21:04,788 --> 00:21:07,957
<i>Hey, hey, wait.
Wait a minute.</i>

264
00:21:08,208 --> 00:21:09,250
Excuse me?

265
00:21:09,876 --> 00:21:11,920
Yeah, that's awesome.

266
00:21:12,087 --> 00:21:15,090
Feeding junk food to forest animals?
That's great.

267
00:21:15,423 --> 00:21:17,383
But, uh, is there
a musical number

268
00:21:17,467 --> 00:21:18,927
where you show me
how to get a tree?

269
00:21:19,135 --> 00:21:20,345
Because I would
love to hear that one.

270
00:21:20,595 --> 00:21:23,389
Oh, yes. Right after the
musical number about the kid

271
00:21:23,556 --> 00:21:25,308
who kept
interrupting the story,

272
00:21:25,391 --> 00:21:27,227
and was never heard from again.

273
00:21:27,811 --> 00:21:29,938
Right, got it. Proceed.

274
00:21:31,481 --> 00:21:33,316
All right, here we go.

275
00:21:33,483 --> 00:21:36,820
About to make a Thneed,
about to change the world.

276
00:22:09,269 --> 00:22:10,562
Check it out, guys...

277
00:22:12,021 --> 00:22:13,106
Where did everybody go?

278
00:22:19,737 --> 00:22:23,074
Little did I know that by
chopping down that tree

279
00:22:23,157 --> 00:22:28,079
I had just summoned a mystical
creature as old as time itself.

280
00:22:28,830 --> 00:22:32,542
The legendary,
slightly annoying

281
00:22:32,709 --> 00:22:34,836
guardian of the forest.

282
00:22:35,628 --> 00:22:37,213
The Lorax.

283
00:24:34,789 --> 00:24:35,832
Hey!
Whoo!

284
00:24:37,333 --> 00:24:38,668
Did you chop down this tree?

285
00:24:39,127 --> 00:24:41,129
Uh... No.

286
00:24:42,296 --> 00:24:43,506
Who did it?

287
00:24:43,798 --> 00:24:45,466
What's that?

288
00:24:47,135 --> 00:24:48,469
I think he did it.

289
00:24:50,805 --> 00:24:52,390
Leave!
Vacate the premises!

290
00:24:52,473 --> 00:24:54,600
Take your ax and get out!

291
00:24:54,767 --> 00:24:57,019
And who are you?

292
00:24:57,770 --> 00:25:01,315
I'm the Lorax!
Guardian of the forest.

293
00:25:01,482 --> 00:25:03,442
I speak for the trees.

294
00:25:05,153 --> 00:25:07,530
So you're telling me,
you just didn't see me

295
00:25:07,613 --> 00:25:09,490
magically appear
out of that stump?

296
00:25:09,657 --> 00:25:11,576
With all the lightning
and thunder and stuff.

297
00:25:11,659 --> 00:25:12,785
You didn't see any of that?

298
00:25:12,869 --> 00:25:15,746
No, but that sounds amazing.
Can I see some of that?

299
00:25:15,913 --> 00:25:19,876
Uh, yeah, I could show you.
But that's not how it works.

300
00:25:20,293 --> 00:25:21,335
Okay. Um...

301
00:25:21,878 --> 00:25:23,004
Didn't really happen.

302
00:25:23,170 --> 00:25:25,756
Oh, I know what you want!

303
00:25:25,840 --> 00:25:32,221
I've got one of these for the
cutest little guy lever saw!

304
00:25:32,388 --> 00:25:35,016
Yummy, yummy,
yummy, yummy, yummy...

305
00:25:35,308 --> 00:25:38,185
How dare you!
Give me that!

306
00:25:38,519 --> 00:25:40,146
Mmm.

307
00:25:40,938 --> 00:25:42,356
I'm going to eat this,

308
00:25:42,440 --> 00:25:44,650
but I am highly offended by it.

309
00:25:50,072 --> 00:25:53,868
What are you... Hey, Mustache!
Will you stop that?

310
00:25:55,369 --> 00:25:57,079
What's your deal, man?

311
00:25:57,204 --> 00:25:59,498
Pull them right out Time
for you to go, Beanpole!

312
00:25:59,707 --> 00:26:01,834
Just going to put them right back in.
We can do this all day.

313
00:26:08,049 --> 00:26:09,425
Stop right there! Stop it!

314
00:26:10,926 --> 00:26:15,931
So you would hammer one of
nature's innocent creatures?

315
00:26:17,516 --> 00:26:18,684
What? No!

316
00:26:18,934 --> 00:26:21,687
I would never hit this little guy.
You, on the other hand,

317
00:26:21,979 --> 00:26:23,189
I would gladly pound you

318
00:26:23,272 --> 00:26:25,066
and your mustache
into the ground!

319
00:26:25,232 --> 00:26:30,029
Behold! The intruder
and his violent ways.

320
00:26:30,112 --> 00:26:33,199
Shame on you.
For shame!

321
00:26:34,408 --> 00:26:36,369
All right, you know what?
That's it!

322
00:26:36,452 --> 00:26:38,371
You listen to me,
you furry meatloaf.

323
00:26:38,454 --> 00:26:40,998
I'm going to chop down as
many trees as I need. Okay?

324
00:26:41,082 --> 00:26:43,417
Newsflash!
Not going anywhere!

325
00:26:44,794 --> 00:26:46,545
End of story.

326
00:26:47,380 --> 00:26:48,839
Then you leave me no choice.

327
00:26:51,967 --> 00:26:56,138
If you're not gone by the time
the sun sets on this valley,

328
00:26:56,222 --> 00:27:00,476
all the forces of nature
will be unleashed upon you

329
00:27:00,768 --> 00:27:05,106
and curse you until
the end of your days!

330
00:27:05,272 --> 00:27:09,110
You have been warned.

331
00:27:15,908 --> 00:27:17,451
Thanks.
Yeah, okay.

332
00:27:17,535 --> 00:27:19,912
You have been warned.

333
00:27:20,871 --> 00:27:23,207
But I didn't listen
to his warning.

334
00:27:23,374 --> 00:27:25,626
And you won't believe
what happened that night.

335
00:27:25,709 --> 00:27:26,752
What?

336
00:27:26,836 --> 00:27:29,004
If you want to hear more,
come back tomorrow.

337
00:27:29,588 --> 00:27:31,590
Hey, wait, wait! Tomorrow?

338
00:27:31,674 --> 00:27:32,967
Whoa!

339
00:27:33,050 --> 00:27:34,760
Whoa-ho-ho.

340
00:27:34,844 --> 00:27:35,970
Are you serious right now?

341
00:27:36,053 --> 00:27:38,681
Ah! You live in
the middle of nowhere!

342
00:27:38,973 --> 00:27:41,350
It stinks out here.
Don't make me come back!

343
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:44,061
I guess you don't really want
to hear the rest of the story.

344
00:27:49,900 --> 00:27:50,985
No, no.

345
00:27:51,360 --> 00:27:54,029
I do. I really do. I want to
hear the story. I just...

346
00:27:54,113 --> 00:27:57,116
Nah! You don't have
what it takes. Goodbye.

347
00:27:57,366 --> 00:27:59,827
Wait, wait!
I have what it takes.

348
00:28:03,539 --> 00:28:05,666
It's all right. It's
okay, I'll come back.

349
00:28:05,749 --> 00:28:06,917
It's no problem.

350
00:28:07,084 --> 00:28:10,921
See, here I am, leaving.
Walking away now.

351
00:28:11,213 --> 00:28:12,548
I'll see you tomorrow.

352
00:28:13,299 --> 00:28:14,383
Mmm.

353
00:28:15,176 --> 00:28:18,387
Maybe. Just maybe.

354
00:28:27,855 --> 00:28:29,315
What did you wish for, Audrey?

355
00:28:29,565 --> 00:28:30,774
Well, I would love to tell you,

356
00:28:30,858 --> 00:28:34,820
but, sadly, according to the
universal wish laws, I cannot.

357
00:28:36,447 --> 00:28:38,282
I know what she wished for.

358
00:28:50,461 --> 00:28:52,171
Was it, perhaps...

359
00:28:53,756 --> 00:28:55,174
This?

360
00:29:03,849 --> 00:29:05,851
Ted, you didn't.

361
00:29:05,935 --> 00:29:09,146
Oh, no. I totally did.

362
00:29:09,313 --> 00:29:12,191
Happy birthday, Audrey.

363
00:29:13,275 --> 00:29:15,110
Kiss him! Kiss him!

364
00:29:28,290 --> 00:29:29,416
Ted.

365
00:29:29,541 --> 00:29:30,876
Ted. Tedster.
Huh!

366
00:29:30,960 --> 00:29:34,213
You're kissing the
cereal again, hon. What?

367
00:29:34,380 --> 00:29:37,216
I just...
I like this cereal.

368
00:29:37,299 --> 00:29:38,509
What one is this?
Yeah!

369
00:29:38,676 --> 00:29:40,260
Okay.

370
00:29:40,427 --> 00:29:43,055
Well, I'll make sure to buy
extra next time for you.

371
00:29:43,305 --> 00:29:45,974
All right, cool. Hey, I got to run.
I got to go do athing.

372
00:29:46,058 --> 00:29:47,726
So, I'll see you guys.

373
00:29:47,976 --> 00:29:49,895
Whoa! Whoa! Whoa!

374
00:29:49,978 --> 00:29:51,772
You're not going
anywhere, young man.

375
00:29:51,939 --> 00:29:54,233
It's Sunday. You
know what that means?

376
00:29:54,400 --> 00:29:57,319
Family time, and we're
all playing board games!

377
00:29:57,403 --> 00:29:58,529
But...

378
00:30:00,572 --> 00:30:01,657
Hmm.

379
00:30:01,740 --> 00:30:03,117
Mmm?

380
00:30:03,617 --> 00:30:04,952
Oh, man.

381
00:30:05,202 --> 00:30:06,912
Mom, seriously every turn?

382
00:30:06,995 --> 00:30:08,664
Hey, back off!

383
00:30:10,165 --> 00:30:11,417
Ooh!

384
00:30:11,500 --> 00:30:14,712
No.
Okay! Family time is over.

385
00:30:14,837 --> 00:30:18,048
It is now personal time.
I'll be in my room.

386
00:30:19,466 --> 00:30:21,885
Okay, dear. Have fun.

387
00:30:24,638 --> 00:30:26,849
I knew I could break her.

388
00:30:27,057 --> 00:30:28,142
Go.
Huh?

389
00:30:28,225 --> 00:30:29,393
Go see him!

390
00:30:29,476 --> 00:30:30,811
Oh, yeah!

391
00:30:32,729 --> 00:30:35,274
You rule!
Thank you, Grammy.

392
00:30:40,112 --> 00:30:41,196
Whoa!

393
00:30:55,794 --> 00:30:57,713
Hey! Ted, right?

394
00:30:58,922 --> 00:31:01,300
Um, Mr. O'Hare?

395
00:31:01,467 --> 00:31:04,678
So, I hear you have
become interested in trees.

396
00:31:04,845 --> 00:31:06,513
What's that all about?

397
00:31:07,097 --> 00:31:08,182
Oh. Um...

398
00:31:09,183 --> 00:31:10,559
Where did you hear that?

399
00:31:10,642 --> 00:31:11,727
Oh.

400
00:31:11,810 --> 00:31:13,562
Teddy, there's not much
that goes on in Thneedville

401
00:31:13,645 --> 00:31:15,439
that I don't know about.

402
00:31:15,522 --> 00:31:19,359
Here's the deal, I make a living
selling fresh air to people.

403
00:31:19,526 --> 00:31:22,070
Trees?
They make it for free.

404
00:31:22,237 --> 00:31:24,990
So, when I hear
people talking about them,

405
00:31:25,073 --> 00:31:28,577
I consider it kind of
a threat to my business.

406
00:31:29,411 --> 00:31:31,455
I don't even know
what you're talking about.

407
00:31:31,580 --> 00:31:33,582
You listen to me, boy.

408
00:31:33,790 --> 00:31:37,252
Don't go poking around in
things you don't understand

409
00:31:37,419 --> 00:31:39,504
or I'll be your
worst nightmare.

410
00:31:39,671 --> 00:31:42,507
I'm Frankenstein's head
on a spider's body!

411
00:31:43,467 --> 00:31:44,760
Yeah, um...

412
00:31:45,886 --> 00:31:47,888
Okay, my mom is expecting me.
So, I'm just going to...

413
00:31:48,722 --> 00:31:52,809
Of course, of course. Now, go
back to your family game time.

414
00:31:53,435 --> 00:31:55,687
Grandma just finished her turn.

415
00:31:56,605 --> 00:31:57,731
How did you know?

416
00:31:58,649 --> 00:32:00,567
Please. I have
eyes everywhere.

417
00:32:05,739 --> 00:32:06,782
Huh!

418
00:32:06,865 --> 00:32:09,326
You got a beautiful
town here, Ted.

419
00:32:09,409 --> 00:32:12,913
Lots of fun stuff to occupy
your short attention span.

420
00:32:13,163 --> 00:32:15,165
Why, I can't
think of any reason

421
00:32:15,332 --> 00:32:20,045
you would ever want to
go outside of town again.

422
00:32:20,128 --> 00:32:21,213
Ever.

423
00:32:26,885 --> 00:32:31,098
Okay! Good talk.
Really good talk.

424
00:32:56,456 --> 00:32:57,499
Oh, no.

425
00:32:58,500 --> 00:32:59,543
Look out!

426
00:33:02,838 --> 00:33:06,383
Hey, man? You know, you need
to change that door bell.

427
00:33:07,050 --> 00:33:09,219
Oh, you missed me.
What?

428
00:33:09,553 --> 00:33:13,682
You're already back. Clearly,
you missed me a little. Right?

429
00:33:13,974 --> 00:33:17,728
No, I didn't. I'm just here
to hear the end of the story.

430
00:33:17,811 --> 00:33:19,521
Why are you so interested
in trees anyway?

431
00:33:19,604 --> 00:33:21,064
Why aren't you like other kids,

432
00:33:21,148 --> 00:33:23,483
break dancing and
wearing bell-bottoms,

433
00:33:23,567 --> 00:33:25,736
and playing the Donkey Kongs?

434
00:33:25,819 --> 00:33:29,573
Yeah, right, right.
I don't know.

435
00:33:30,073 --> 00:33:34,327
Uh, I just thought it would be kind
of cool to have one, you know?

436
00:33:34,536 --> 00:33:35,704
Huh?

437
00:33:35,787 --> 00:33:37,330
It's a girl, isn't it?

438
00:33:37,664 --> 00:33:39,332
What? No!

439
00:33:39,666 --> 00:33:42,335
Really? Because when a guy
does something stupid once,

440
00:33:42,419 --> 00:33:44,045
well, that's because
he's a guy.

441
00:33:44,129 --> 00:33:46,673
But if he does
the same stupid thing twice,

442
00:33:46,756 --> 00:33:49,509
it's usually to
impress some girl.

443
00:33:49,801 --> 00:33:51,511
Hey, she is not some girl!

444
00:33:51,595 --> 00:33:54,639
She's a woman, in high school.

445
00:33:54,806 --> 00:33:57,893
And she loves trees.
And I'm going to get her one.

446
00:33:58,101 --> 00:33:59,311
Aw!

447
00:33:59,394 --> 00:34:03,398
How nice to see someone so
undeterred by things like reality.

448
00:34:03,523 --> 00:34:04,608
Thank you.

449
00:34:04,691 --> 00:34:06,610
All right,
but where did we leave off?

450
00:34:28,089 --> 00:34:30,467
Now that's a Thneed.

451
00:34:30,634 --> 00:34:33,386
Nothing unmanly
about knitting. No, sir.

452
00:34:55,659 --> 00:34:56,743
Look at that...

453
00:34:58,078 --> 00:34:59,120
Oh!

454
00:34:59,204 --> 00:35:01,206
Who taught you guys
how to steal a bed?

455
00:35:06,503 --> 00:35:07,754
Shh!

456
00:35:27,524 --> 00:35:29,609
Okay, nice and easy.

457
00:35:36,616 --> 00:35:39,786
Nice work, you guys. Couldn't
have done it without you.

458
00:35:42,288 --> 00:35:45,625
You got to be kidding me.
Can he swim?

459
00:35:46,418 --> 00:35:47,585
Of course he can't swim!

460
00:35:47,877 --> 00:35:50,547
Hang on, Pipsqueak!
I'm coming to get you!

461
00:35:55,677 --> 00:35:57,721
Hey, you fishies!
Stop that bed!

462
00:36:02,392 --> 00:36:04,019
Whoo! Whoo!

463
00:36:09,065 --> 00:36:10,525
Jump, jump!

464
00:36:11,109 --> 00:36:12,944
Come on, get up there.
Come on.

465
00:36:13,361 --> 00:36:15,989
Go, go! A little bit more!
A little bit more!

466
00:36:18,867 --> 00:36:20,201
Now what?

467
00:36:21,911 --> 00:36:23,121
Mmm-mmm.

468
00:36:24,247 --> 00:36:25,749
Get up there.

469
00:36:28,460 --> 00:36:30,003
Okay, Pipsqueak,
give me your hand.

470
00:36:30,086 --> 00:36:31,129
Come on,
reach out for the Lorax.

471
00:36:34,966 --> 00:36:36,217
Where did you go?

472
00:36:39,512 --> 00:36:40,764
Bar-ba-loots.

473
00:36:49,439 --> 00:36:50,565
Oh, that's bad.

474
00:36:55,111 --> 00:36:56,613
Hey, Beanpole, wake up!

475
00:37:06,080 --> 00:37:08,041
What's happening?
Where am I?

476
00:37:08,124 --> 00:37:11,544
Hey! We got trouble,
and it's coming up fast!

477
00:37:14,214 --> 00:37:15,256
Whoo!

478
00:37:15,340 --> 00:37:16,841
We're in a river!

479
00:37:35,276 --> 00:37:36,319
Whew!

480
00:37:40,573 --> 00:37:41,741
Oh, no.

481
00:37:44,953 --> 00:37:46,412
Just do something!

482
00:37:47,539 --> 00:37:49,123
Help is on the way!

483
00:37:52,168 --> 00:37:53,795
No, no!

484
00:37:55,421 --> 00:37:56,673
Just a minute!

485
00:38:18,152 --> 00:38:19,237
Oh, no!

486
00:38:22,991 --> 00:38:24,284
Wake up! Wake up!

487
00:38:25,326 --> 00:38:27,453
Yuck!

488
00:38:32,583 --> 00:38:33,710
Clear!

489
00:38:33,793 --> 00:38:35,003
Ah!

490
00:38:38,047 --> 00:38:39,590
I was heading into the light,

491
00:38:39,674 --> 00:38:41,592
and you pulled me
right back and here I am!

492
00:38:41,884 --> 00:38:43,219
You saved my life!

493
00:38:43,303 --> 00:38:46,222
Yeah, I know. Well, no,
it's not that big a deal.

494
00:38:46,306 --> 00:38:47,473
It is a big deal!

495
00:38:47,682 --> 00:38:51,728
Look, I almost went over
that waterfall! Wait...

496
00:38:52,437 --> 00:38:55,189
On my bed. How did my
bed get in the river?

497
00:38:55,314 --> 00:38:57,984
Uh... About that...

498
00:38:58,735 --> 00:39:02,655
Actually... I put your
bed in the water.

499
00:39:03,364 --> 00:39:04,866
I didn't mean you any harm.

500
00:39:04,949 --> 00:39:07,452
I just wanted to
calmly float you away.

501
00:39:08,453 --> 00:39:10,913
Look, everyone here
needs the trees

502
00:39:10,997 --> 00:39:13,124
and you're chopping them down!

503
00:39:13,833 --> 00:39:17,211
So, we've got a big problem.

504
00:39:23,342 --> 00:39:24,427
All right, look.

505
00:39:24,594 --> 00:39:28,931
I hereby swear that I will
never chop down another tree.

506
00:39:30,016 --> 00:39:31,559
I promise.

507
00:39:32,101 --> 00:39:35,313
Thank you. But I'm going
to keep my eye on you.

508
00:39:35,772 --> 00:39:37,815
Good. Now, I've got
a big day tomorrow

509
00:39:37,899 --> 00:39:39,734
so I'm going to get some sleep.

510
00:39:42,737 --> 00:39:44,947
Right after I find my bed.

511
00:40:05,802 --> 00:40:06,844
Ow!

512
00:40:06,928 --> 00:40:09,096
Okay, what are you...

513
00:40:10,807 --> 00:40:12,850
Question, what are
